<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-431-218  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 431 218.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Object-Oriented Programming  March-April 1990 v2 n6p63(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cooperating methods in CLOS. (CLOS) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Keene, Sonya E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Programmers working in CLOS can define methods that work togethercooperatively to take advantage of multiple inheritance.andP;  Thereare different roles for CLOS methods: primary, before, and after.andO;The primary method does most of the work and returns the values ofthe generic function.andP;  The before method does some work before theprimary runs.andP;  The after method performs some work after theprimary runs.andP;  The generic function's framework defines whichroles are supported, how the methods are combined, and how thevalues are computed.andP;  CLOS supports both declarative andimperative techniques.andP;  The programmer who uses the declarativetechnique looks at each method as an independent unit.andP;  Theprogrammer who uses the imperative technique can usearound-methods to wrap around other methods and call them.andP;  Thereare a number of frameworks: the standard one which supports beforemethods, after methods, primary methods, and around methods; thelist framework, the + framework, and the or framework.andP;  Thedefine-method-combination macros permits users to define morecomplicated frameworks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Object-Oriented ProgrammingProgrammingMethods.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Relationships between classes. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>